4. Lucretius’ View of Man.

In man, as in all things else, there is nothing but matter and void. The human organism comprises three distinct parts, the body, the soul or life-principle, and the mind. These originate‚ develop‚ decline, and perish together, for the mind and soul are inseparably united with each other and with the body.⁸ The mind is situated in the mid-region of the breast, while the soul is distributed throughout the form3 but the mind and soul are so closely connected that they may be considered as one nature.
